def text_analysis(dataset, dataset_name):
    print(f"\nThis is the shape of the dataset {dataset_name}:")
    print(dataset.shape)

    print(f"\nThis is the index of the dataset {dataset_name}:")
    print(dataset.index)

    print(f"\nThese are the columns in the dataset {dataset_name}:")
    print(dataset.columns)

    print(f"\nThe total number of non-NA values in the dataset {dataset_name}:")
    print(dataset.notna().sum())

    print(f"\nA summary of the dataset {dataset_name} is shown below:")
    print(dataset.info())

    print(f"\nA descriptive statistical summary of the dataset {dataset_name} is shown below:")
    print(dataset.describe())

Nature Of The Dataset:¶

The CSV file "graduate-employment-survey-ntu-nus-sit-smu-suss-sutd" contains data on the employment outcomes of graduates from the six autonomous universities in Singapore (NUS, NTU, SMU, SUTD, SIT, and SUSS). The data includes the following columns:

  • Year: The year in which the graduate graduated.
  • University: The university from which the graduate graduated.
  • School: The school within the university from which the graduate graduated.
  • Degree: The degree that the graduate graduated with.
  • Employment_rate_overall: The overall employment rate of graduates from the university.
  • Employment_rate_ft_perm: The full-time permanent employment rate of graduates from the university.
  • Basic_monthly_mean: The mean basic monthly salary of graduates from the university.
  • Basic_monthly_median: The median basic monthly salary of graduates from the university.
  • Gross_monthly_mean: The mean gross monthly salary of graduates from the university.
  • Gross_monthly_median: The median gross monthly salary of graduates from the university.
  • Gross_mthly_25_percentile: The 25th percentile of the gross monthly salaries of graduates from the university.
  • Gross_mthly_75_percentile: The 75th percentile of the gross monthly salaries of graduates from the university.

The dataset contains a total of 1121 rows of data. The data is relatively clean and well-formatted. However, there are a few peculiarities that should be noted.

  • The data does not include information on the gender of the graduates. This information would be useful for understanding the differences in employment outcomes between male and female graduates.
  • The data does not include information on the race of the graduates. This information would also be useful for understanding the differences in employment outcomes between different racial groups.
  • The data does not include information on the undergraduate GPA of the graduates. This information would be useful for understanding the relationship between undergraduate GPA and employment outcomes.
  • It is also to be noted that the number of graduates surveyed for each university is different, NTU & NUS graduates accounted for most of the surveys conducted.

I analyzed the dataset using the following steps:

  1. I imported the data into a Python Pandas DataFrame.
  2. I performed a statistical analysis of the data, including calculating the mean, range of the employment rates, basic monthly salaries.
  3. I created visualizations of the data, such as line charts, bar charts, box plots, and scatterplots.
  4. I interpreted the results of the analysis to identify trends and patterns in the data.

What is the trend of the mean basic monthly salary over the years for local universities in Sinagpore ?¶

# Clean the data and convert numeric columns to appropriate data types
numeric_columns = ['employment_rate_overall', 'employment_rate_ft_perm', 'basic_monthly_mean', 'basic_monthly_median', 'gross_monthly_mean', 'gross_monthly_median', 'gross_mthly_25_percentile', 'gross_mthly_75_percentile']
graduate_employment_survey_ntu_nus_sit_smu_suss_sutd[numeric_columns] = graduate_employment_survey_ntu_nus_sit_smu_suss_sutd[numeric_columns].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce')

# Group the data by university and year, and calculate the mean salary for each university in each year
grouped_data = cleaned_data.groupby(["university", "year"])["basic_monthly_mean"].mean().reset_index()

# Create a line chart to show the trend of mean salaries over the years for each university
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

universities = grouped_data["university"].unique()

for university in universities:
    data_by_university = grouped_data[grouped_data["university"] == university]
    plt.plot(data_by_university["year"], data_by_university["basic_monthly_mean"], label=university)

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Mean Basic Monthly Salary(SGD)')
plt.title('Trend of Mean Basic Monthly Salary Over the Years for Each University')
plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

From the line chart, it shows the Trend of Mean Basic Monthly Salary Over the Years for Each University. It is evident that there is a notable relationship between the passage of time and the increase in mean basic monthly salary for all universities. There is also a steep increase in basic monthly salary between 2018-2019 for NUS(around SGD3700 to around SGD4000), 2020-2021 for SMU(around SGD4300 to around SGD4600) & SUSS(around SGD3200 to around SGD3450). In 2021, the lowest basic monthly salary would be around SGD3450 for SUSS and the highest would be be around SGD4600 for SMU.

How does the mean basic monthly salary correlate with the employment rate?¶

In [96]:
# Clean the data and convert numeric columns to appropriate data types
numeric_columns = ['employment_rate_overall', 'employment_rate_ft_perm', 'basic_monthly_mean', 'basic_monthly_median', 'gross_monthly_mean', 'gross_monthly_median', 'gross_mthly_25_percentile', 'gross_mthly_75_percentile']
graduate_employment_survey_ntu_nus_sit_smu_suss_sutd[numeric_columns] = graduate_employment_survey_ntu_nus_sit_smu_suss_sutd[numeric_columns].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce')

# Drop rows with NaN values in the 'basic_monthly_mean' & 'employment_rate_ft_perm' column
cleaned_data = graduate_employment_survey_ntu_nus_sit_smu_suss_sutd.dropna(subset=['basic_monthly_mean', 'employment_rate_ft_perm'])

# Basic monthly salary vs. employment rate
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.scatter(cleaned_data['employment_rate_ft_perm'], cleaned_data['basic_monthly_mean'], marker='o', c='b', label='Data Points')

# Calculate the best-fit line (linear regression)
coefficients = np.polyfit(cleaned_data['employment_rate_ft_perm'], cleaned_data['basic_monthly_mean'], 1)
poly_function = np.poly1d(coefficients)
x_values = cleaned_data['employment_rate_ft_perm']
y_fit = poly_function(x_values)

# Plot the best-fit line
plt.plot(x_values, y_fit, color='r', label='Best Fit Line')

plt.xlabel('Full-Time Employment Rate (%)')
plt.ylabel('Basic Monthly Salary(SGD)')
plt.title('Full-Time Employment Rate vs. Basic Monthly Salary (2013-2021)')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

From the scatterplot, it shows the relationship between basic monthly salary and the full-time employment rate . It is the highest at 100% employment rate with just around SGD3800. This is because when everyone who graduates is employed full-time, the demand for labor is high, which drives up wages. It is the lowest at around 30% employment rate with just around SGD2900. This is because when there are fewer jobs available, the competition for those jobs is fierce, which drives down wages. It is evident that there is a positive correlation between the full-time employment rate and the basic monthly salary. As the full-time employment rate increases, the basic monthly salary also tends to increase.

When the demand for labor is high, the basic monthly salary is high. When the demand for labor is low, the basic monthly salary is low.

Insights gained from analysing the data¶

I have analyzed the data in the CSV file "graduate-employment-survey-ntu-nus-sit-smu-suss-sutd". Here are some insights I have gained:

  • The average employment rate of graduates from the six autonomous universities in Singapore has increased over time. This is likely due to a number of factors, including the strong economic growth in Singapore, the increasing demand for skilled workers, and the government's efforts to improve the job market for graduates.
  • The average basic monthly salary of graduates from the six autonomous universities in Singapore has also increased over time. This is likely due to the same factors that have led to the increase in the average employment rate.
  • There is a positive correlation between the full-time employment rate and the basic monthly salary. This means that as the full-time employment rate increases, the basic monthly salary also tends to increase.
  • There is a difference in the average basic monthly salary across the six autonomous universities in Singapore. SMU has the highest average basic monthly salary, followed by NUS, NTU, SUTD, SIT, and SUSS.
  • NTU and SUTD have outliers in the distribution of the basic monthly salary. This means that there are some graduates from these universities who are earning significantly more than the average.

Based on my analysis, I have the following conclusions and recommendations:

  • The strong economic growth in Singapore is likely to continue in the coming years, which will lead to an increase in the demand for skilled workers. This will in turn lead to an increase in the average employment rate and basic monthly salary of graduates from the six autonomous universities in Singapore.
  • The government's efforts to improve the job market for graduates are also likely to continue in the coming years. This will help to ensure that graduates from the six autonomous universities in Singapore are able to find good jobs and earn competitive salaries.
  • Students who are considering attending one of the six autonomous universities in Singapore should be aware of the different average basic monthly salaries across the universities. This will help them to choose a university that is a good fit for their financial goals.

Here are some additional insights that could be gained from the data:

  • SUSS has the lowest variance in the distribution of the basic monthly salary. This means that the basic monthly salaries of graduates from SUSS are more evenly distributed.
  • NUS and SIT have a huge variance in the distribution of the basic monthly salary. This means that there are a large number of graduates from these universities who are earning significantly more than the average, and a large number of graduates who are earning significantly less than the average.
  • The analysis of the dataset provides valuable insights into the employment outcomes of graduates from the six autonomous universities in Singapore. The findings of the analysis can be used by prospective students, parents, and employers to make informed decisions about education and career planning.

Nature Of The Dataset:¶

The CSV file "government-recurrent-expenditure-on-education-per-student" contains data on government recurrent expenditure on education per student in Singapore from Jan 2019 to Dec 2022. The data includes the following columns:

  • Year: The year in which the expenditure was made.
  • Type of educational institution: The type of educational institution, such as primary school, secondary school, polytechnic, or university.
  • Expenditure per student: The amount of government recurrent expenditure per student in that institution in that year.

The dataset contains a total of 216 rows of data. The data is relatively clean and well-formatted. However, there are a few peculiarities that should be noted.

  • The data does not include information on the number of students enrolled in each type of educational institution. This information would be useful for understanding the relative impact of the government's expenditure on each type of institution.

I analyzed the dataset using the following steps:

  1. I imported the data into a Python Numpy DataFrame.
  2. I performed a statistical analysis of the data, including calculating the mean, of the expenditure per student by type of educational institution.
  3. I created visualizations of the data, such as line chart, bar graph, pie chart and boxplots.
  4. I interpreted the results of the analysis to identify trends and patterns in the data.

Nature Of The Dataset:¶

The CSV file "Universities - Intake, Enrolment and Graduates by Course" contains data on the intake, enrolment, and graduates of different courses offered by universities in Singapore. The data includes the following columns:

  • year: The year in which the course was offered.
  • sex: The gender of the students enrolled in the course.
  • course: The name of the course.
  • intake: The number of students admitted to the course.
  • enrolment: The number of students enrolled in the course.
  • graduates: The number of students who graduated from the course.

The dataset contains a total of 510 rows of data. The data is relatively clean and well-formatted. However, there are a few peculiarities that should be noted.

  • The data does not include information on the race of the students. This information would be useful for understanding the differences in enrollment and graduation rates between different racial groups.
  • The data does not include information on the undergraduate GPA of the students. This information would be useful for understanding the relationship between undergraduate GPA and enrollment and graduation rates.
  • Universities refers to National University of Singapore, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore Management University, Singapore Institute of Technology, Singapore University of Technology & Design and Singapore University of Social Sciences.
  • Intake, enrolment and graduates figures refer to full-time first degree only.

Nature Of The Dataset:¶

The CSV files under "world_happiness_report" contains data on the happniess scores of each country. The data includes the following MAIN columns:

  • Rank: The rank of happiness score across the world.
  • Country: The country.
  • Happiness Score: The happiness scores of each country.

The data is relatively clean and well-formatted. However, there are a few peculiarities that should be noted.

  • Each dataset belongs to different years and hence have various columns, but ultimately show the rank as well as the happiness score of each country

I analyzed the dataset using the following steps:

  1. I imported the data into a Python Numpy DataFrame.
  2. I performed a statistical analysis of the data,bar graphs.
  3. I created visualizations of the data, such as line chart, bar graph and histogram.
  4. I interpreted the results of the analysis to identify trends and patterns in the data.

What are the top 3 happiest countires ?¶

In [117]:
# Remove the commas from the happiness score and divide by 1000 to get a more readable number
world_happiness_2022['Happiness score'] = world_happiness_2022['Happiness score'].str.replace(",", "").astype(float) / 1000

# Top 3 countries by happiness score for each year
happiness_cond_2019 = world_happiness_2019.head(3)
happiness_cond_2020 = world_happiness_2020.head(3)
happiness_cond_2021 = world_happiness_2021.head(3)
happiness_cond_2022 = world_happiness_2022.head(3)

# Include Singapore in the top 3 countries for 2022
sg_2019 = world_happiness_2019[world_happiness_2019['Country or region'] == 'Singapore']
happiness_cond_2019 = pd.concat([happiness_cond_2019, sg_2019])

sg_2020 = world_happiness_2020[world_happiness_2020['Country name'] == 'Singapore']
happiness_cond_2020 = pd.concat([happiness_cond_2020, sg_2020])

sg_2021 = world_happiness_2021[world_happiness_2021['Country name'] == 'Singapore']
happiness_cond_2021 = pd.concat([happiness_cond_2021, sg_2021])

sg_2022 = world_happiness_2022[world_happiness_2022['Country'] == 'Singapore']
happiness_cond_2022 = pd.concat([happiness_cond_2022, sg_2022])

# Keeping only the 'Country' and 'Happiness score' columns.
happiness_cond_2022 = happiness_cond_2022.filter(['Country', 'Happiness score'])
# Adding a year column to each dataframe
happiness_cond_2022['year'] = 2022
# Setting the index to year
happiness_cond_2022.set_index('year', inplace=True)
# Renaming the columns to match the other dataframes
happiness_cond_2022.rename(columns={'Country': 'country', 'Happiness score': 'score'}, inplace=True)

happiness_cond_2021 = happiness_cond_2021.filter(['Country name', 'Ladder score'])
happiness_cond_2021['year'] = 2021
happiness_cond_2021.set_index('year', inplace=True)
happiness_cond_2021.rename(columns={'Country name': 'country', 'Ladder score': 'score'}, inplace=True)

happiness_cond_2020 = happiness_cond_2020.filter(['Country name', 'Ladder score'])
happiness_cond_2020['year'] = 2020
happiness_cond_2020.set_index('year', inplace=True)
happiness_cond_2020.rename(columns={'Country name': 'country', 'Ladder score': 'score'}, inplace=True)

Nature Of The Dataset:¶

The CSV file "total-government-expenditure-on-education-gdp" contains data on the total government expenditure on education as a percentage of GDP for different countries. The data includes the following columns:

  • Entity: The name of the country.
  • Code: The country code.
  • Year: The year of the data.
  • "Government expenditure on education, total (% of GDP)": The total government expenditure on education as a percentage of GDP.

The dataset contains a total of 227 rows of data. The data is relatively clean and well-formatted. However, there are a few peculiarities that should be noted.

  • The data does not include information on the specific levels of education that the government expenditure is allocated to. This information would be useful for understanding how the government expenditure is distributed across different levels of education.
  • The data does not include information on the sources of government revenue that are used to fund education. This information would be useful for understanding the impact of different tax policies on education spending.

I analyzed the dataset using the following steps:

  1. I imported the data into a Python Pandas DataFrame.
  2. I performed a statistical analysis of the data, including calculating the mean, median, and range of the government expenditure on education as a percentage of GDP.
  3. I created visualizations of the data, such as line charts, bar charts, pie charts, and scatterplots.
  4. I interpreted the results of the analysis to identify trends and patterns in the data.

Final Data Analysis Conclusion¶

The analysis of international data on intelligence (IQ) and happiness scores revealed interesting patterns. The top five countries with the highest IQ scores are all from the Asian region, while the bottom five countries are from the African region, except for Guatemala (Central America) and Nepal (Asia). Additionally, the analysis showed a positive correlation between a country's GDP and its happiness index and IQ ranking. Countries with higher GDP tended to have higher happiness scores and IQ rankings. It can also be seen that countries who have a lower GDP tend to have a higher variance in terms of the percentage of gdp spent of education.

In conclusion, the data analysis highlights the importance of education in improving employment rates and basic monthly salaries. It suggests that investing in education can have positive effects on intelligence and, consequently, on happiness.

Overall, the data analysis provides valuable insights into the impact of education on intelligence and happiness, laying the foundation for informed decision-making in policy and personal choices.
